1 Historical Background
Gouy’s Method, also known as Gouy’s magnetic susceptibility balance was developed
by French physicist Louis Georges Gouy in the late 19th century. The main purpose
of Gouy balance is for measuring the magnetic susceptibility of materials. During the
late 19th century, scientists were intrigued by the magnetic properties of matter, mainly
paramagnetic materials. In simple words, paramagnetic materials were substances which
are attracted by magnetic ﬁeld and have positive magnetic susceptibilities. It was based
on the principle that when a paramagnetic substance is placed in a non-uniform ﬁeld, it
experiences a magnetic force that causes it to move within a tube or container. The basic
equation to formulate susceptibility is-
M = χH
where M is the magnetic moment per unit volume, and H is the magnetizing ﬁeld, χ is
the magnetic susceptibility and is a tensor. For paramagnetic substances, the M and H
are parallel, giving rise to a positive magnetic susceptibility. Even though there are other
methods like Quincke’s method for measuring magnetic susceptibility, they don’t provide
precise measurements like Gouy method as they require a salt solution to be prepared.
Still, Gouy Method is just a classical technique and modern labs have replaced it with
advanced methods like vibrating sample magnetometers (VSM) and superconducting
quantum interference devices (SQUIDs). However, it played a crucial role in the early
understanding of magnetic properties and contributed to the development of modern
magnetometry techniques.

3 Discussion
3.1 Sources of error and precautions
• Disturbance to the setup due to surroundings can aﬀect the balance for weight
measurement because it is very sensitive. We avoid disturbance to a large degree
by keeping the sample inside an isolated box with glass doors. And also perform
the experiment when very few people are present.
• Eﬀect of the residual magnetic ﬁeld can generate error in the data.
3.2 Observation and conclusion
• The increase in the weight of the sample increases linearly with the increasing
magnetic ﬁeld squared.
• The sample is paramagnetic in nature as we see an increase in the weight with
increasing magnetic ﬁeld.
• The required speciﬁc susceptibility of the sample is 32.01 x 10
